      "text": "# Die Gewalt des Terrorismus"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "bb275a2066b2f62d",
      "text": "Perceptual readinesses can be socially directed insofar as the typicality of the expectations associated with them makes them candidates for structural coupling. Interactions themselves hardly have the possibility to deal with these horizon problems. But they can be shaped - for example by organization. The experiential lifeworld can be shaped in such a way that specific perceptual readiness for certain events, now to be excluded in the pursuit of a theme, is formed and incorporated into situational horizons. Attempts at the social use of this category of orientation can be observed, for example, in the case of bouncers in discotheques or in the case of security measures at airports, etc. In these cases, where violence is more likely to be expected, the inclusion of the violence to be excluded can be symbolized by staging activities. But terrorist violence operates covertly. It attempts to circumnavigate even the perceptual predispositions of its potential victims and mandated debunkers.60 Suddenly, suitcases or backpacks with no discernible owner may take on an alarm character. Organizational decision-based as well as society-wide communicative efforts to somehow nevertheless maintain system trust in this new situation increase in number and intensity. Among other things, there are hectic attempts to uncover hidden commitments or to publicly symbolize efforts in this direction, or attempts to normalize the connection between attention and intention in interactions through attempts to shape related perceptual readiness, which make it possible for us in everyday life to refrain from the danger that the violence of terrorism will be repeated in order to be able to turn our attention to other topics."
    },
